  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Waiting Too Long for LAMal</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You have 3 months to arrange LAMal, but don't wait. If you miss the deadline, the canton assigns you a provider—usually at higher rates with less choice. Arrange insurance in your first month to avoid stress and get the best rates.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Comparing Cantons for Cost of Living</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Geneva can cost CHF 200/month more than Zug for identical LAMal coverage. If your job allows flexible location, choosing a cheaper canton saves thousands annually. Consider commuting from lower-cost cantons to major cities.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing Wrong Franchise Level</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Young, healthy people often save CHF 1,500+/year with CHF 2,500 franchise. But if you have ongoing medical needs, CHF 300 franchise may cost less overall. Do the math based on your actual healthcare usage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Non-EU Applicants Missing Quota Timing</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Quotas reset in November. Applying in September for a January start is risky—slots may be gone. If you're non-EU, time your job search for fall applications. Major employers know to submit early; smaller companies may not.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Registering Within 14 Days</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register at the commune (Einwohnerkontrolle) within 14 days of moving in. Without registration, you can't get your residence permit card, open bank accounts easily, or complete many administrative tasks. Don't delay.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Switzerland -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Switzerland</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Swiss healthcare is world-class with short wait times and excellent facilities. The system is private but heavily regulated. With LAMal, you have access to any Swiss doctor or hospital. Quality is consistent across the country.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Swiss Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hausarzt (GP) Model</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Most people register with a Hausarzt (family doctor) who coordinates care. Some LAMal models require GP referral for specialist visits (HMO/Hausarzt models) in exchange for lower premiums.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">With standard LAMal, you can see specialists directly. Wait times are short—usually days to weeks, not months. Urban areas have more specialists; rural areas may require travel.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">LAMal covers general ward (shared rooms). Supplementary insurance upgrades to semi-private or private rooms. Major hospitals in Zurich, Geneva, Basel, Bern are excellent. Emergency care (Notfall) is available 24/7.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Pharmacies (Apotheken)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Prescription medications are partially covered by LAMal after your franchise. Swiss pharmacists are highly trained and can advise on minor issues. Prices are higher than neighboring countries.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Finding English-Speaking Doctors</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      In Zurich, Geneva, and Basel, many doctors speak English. International communities are well-served. Use doctor search tools from your insurer or platforms like Doctolib.ch. In German-speaking areas, having basic German helps for medical discussions.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Cross-border care:</strong> Some Swiss LAMal plans cover treatment in neighboring countries (France, Germany, Italy, Austria). This can be useful for cheaper dental work or if you live near borders. Check your specific policy for EU treatment rules.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why doesn't my Swiss employer provide health insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Switzerland's system is individual-based, not employer-based. Everyone must buy their own LAMal. This actually provides portability—you keep your insurance between jobs. Employers may offer supplementary benefits but not basic LAMal.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between franchise levels?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Franchise is your annual deductible (CHF 300 to CHF 2,500). Higher franchise = lower monthly premium. After paying your franchise, you pay 10% of remaining costs (capped at CHF 700/year). Healthy people usually save money with CHF 2,500 franchise.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can non-EU citizens get work permits?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but it's harder. Employers must prove no EU candidate is suitable (labor market test), and annual quotas apply (~8,500 B permits). Highly skilled workers in shortage occupations have best chances. Major companies are experienced with the process.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until permanent residence (C Permit)?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          EU/EFTA citizens: 5 years of continuous residence. Non-EU citizens: 10 years (5 years for US, Canada, and some other nationalities by treaty). C Permit holders have permanent residence rights and don't need renewal.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me in Switzerland?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouse and children under 18 can join on family reunion permits. They have work rights. Each family member needs their own LAMal—budget accordingly. Children have lower premiums (often subsidized by cantons for lower incomes).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I lose my job?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          B Permit holders have a grace period (usually 3-6 months) to find new employment. You may be eligible for unemployment benefits (RAV) if you've contributed. Your LAMal continues—you pay it yourself. If unemployed long-term, permit may not be renewed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Switzerland offers unmatched salaries and quality of life, but requires careful planning around health insurance. The LAMal system is different from other countries—no employer coverage, mandatory personal purchase, significant canton variations. Understanding the franchise system and comparing providers can save thousands annually.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For EU/EFTA citizens, the permit process is straightforward. For non-EU workers, securing a permit requires an employer who can justify the hire and timing applications for quota availability. The effort is worth it for those who qualify—Swiss salaries and stability are exceptional.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Budget CHF 300-600/month for LAMal depending on your canton and franchise choice. Live in a cheaper canton if possible. Choose high franchise if healthy. Compare providers at priminfo.admin.ch. Arrange insurance promptly after arrival—don't wait for the 3-month deadline.
    </p>

